    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "The main objective is to learn the fundamental principles and operation of optoelectronic devices to isolate the input system from the output system and the special configurations needed when working with AC or DC sources."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Optocouplers\nAn optocoupler combines, on the same base, an LED and a photodetector. Figure 1\nshows an optocoupler formed by an LED and a photodiode; the first is on the left and the\nsecond, on the right, the voltage that feeds the LED causes it to emit light that will affect\nthe photodiode. The light striking the photodiode creates a reverse current that passes\nthrough resistor R2. The photodiode voltage is:\nsal ss 2 V = V - IR\nThis output voltage will depend on the magnitude of the reverse current. If the\nvoltage feeding the LED is modified, the light intensity, the photodiode current and,\nconsequently, Vout vary. If the LED current has a variation of AC, Vout will have the same\nvariation of AC\nThe main advantage of the optocoupler is the electrical isolation between the LED\ncircuit and the photodiode circuit; It is common for the resistance between the input circuit\nand the output circuit to be greater than 1010 Ω. For this reason, the optocoupler is also\nknown as an \"optoisolator\"; the only contact between the input and output circuits is the\nlight beam."
