      }), "\n", _jsx(_components.li, {
        children: "Procedure:\nEXPERIMENT 1: Optocoupler\n• To investigate the data sheet of the used optocoupler.\n• To assemble the circuit of figure 2 a) and b), set the voltage source to 2 V. Measure and record the output voltage (table 1). Attention the ground of the LED is different from the ground of the output, the circuits are being isolated!\n• Repeat step 2 for the power supply voltages listed in table1.\n• To plot the Vout in function of the Vs transfer plot of the optocoupler with the data from Table 1 in Graph 1.\nVs (V)\nVout (V)\n2\n4\n6\n8\n10\n12\n14\nTable 1 of optocoupler\nFigure 2: a) Circuit of an optocoupler, A) with 4N26, B) with PC817\nEXPERIMENT 2: Circuits with optocouplers for lighting LEDs\n• To investigate the data sheet of the used optocoupler\n• To reproduce the circuits in figure 3 a) and b) and try the push buttons. Write down the values of the DC multimeters\nFigura 3: a) Circuito de un optoacoplador, A) con 4N26, B) com PC817\nEXPERIMENT 3: Optocoupler circuits with TRIAC to power loads that draw alternating current (AC)\n• To investigate the data sheet of the optocoupler used\n• To reproduce the circuits in figure 4 and try the push buttons.\nFigure 4: Circuit of an optocoupler with a MOC3021 triac"
      }), "\n"]
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "An optocoupler is an electronic component that transfers a signal between two isolated circuits using light. They are used to isolate parts of the system to prevent high voltages from affecting the rest of the components that receive the signal. Generally it is the combination of a light emitter, for example a LED, and photosensitive device like a photodetector. The incoming signal will determine the LED's brightness that will then be interpreted by the photodetector to recover the original signal as its output."
